00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:22.000
I want to start off by talking about how the process of data science is, in many ways,

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:28.000
different from the process of what you might call general purpose software engineering.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:35.000
The process of data analysis, working with data, is iterative and exploratory.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.000
So, we definitely use code.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:39.000
We write code to analyze data.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:46.000
But the process of writing code for the specific purpose of analyzing data, it's substantially

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:52.000
different from what someone is doing who is writing code, maybe to build a website.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
Or maybe to make a mobile app or something.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:01.000
This diagram outlines one model for what that process of data science may be like.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:04.000
You start, the first thing you do, you read in some data.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Maybe you read from a CSV, or maybe you read from a database.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.000
You have some data in memory, in Python.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
And then you start, actually, in what is, I believe, an iterative set of steps.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.000
You maybe reshape the data.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.000
You munch the data.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Maybe you make a visualization to see what's in there.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Then you use that to maybe train a model or to train a first version of a model.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:37.000
And you realize, oh, I should, you know, maybe use this variable I have with some feature

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.000
engineering.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.000
And you go around.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.000
Or maybe you're like, ah, this doesn't make sense.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Let me go back to that variable I was using and look in more detail.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:51.000
And, oh, I have to correct for this way that the data was recorded.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:53.000
And so, then you transform again.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:55.000
You make another visualization.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Then you go back to your model again.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:06.000
And this process, the important thing is you don't know what the next step is until you see what's really in the data.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:14.000
And so, this process, you probably would actually make mistakes if you, ahead of time, said exactly what you would do

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
and did not stray from that path.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:23.000
Because when we're doing statistical analysis, machine learning, data analysis of various kinds,

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
we're coming up against the real world.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:26.000
The real world.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:31.000
And we have to iterate in a way because of the actual content of the data that we're working with.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:38.000
And this is unique about the work of what people doing data analytics, data science, machine learning.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.000
It's a unique characteristic of what this kind of work is like.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:44.000
Eventually, you do decide you're done.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Or at least you're like, ah, I got to stop.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:52.000
I can't keep iterating on this model or app or plot or whatever it is you're trying to make.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:53.000
You decide you're done.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:56.000
And then you do something with that analysis.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Largely, we communicate about it.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
We write a report.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
We build an interactive app of some kind.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Maybe we deploy a model and then have to tell people about the model.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:13.000
But this idea of what data science is like, what working with data is like,

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:18.000
is an important thing for us to keep in mind as we're thinking about our practices,

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:23.000
as we're thinking about our tools and the kind of tools we choose to use.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:31.000
A result of this kind of iterative, exploratory nature of data work is that we end up in a situation

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:35.000
where we are making a lot of decisions.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:41.000
We're making a lot of decisions, and the one decision we make depends on the last decision we made.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:47.000
People, when they talk about this, they talk about it with the idea of like a labyrinth or a maze

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:52.000
or there's this paper that's called The Garden of Forking Paths.

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
The Garden of Forking Paths.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:00.000
It's the idea that I'm walking through a garden, and there are all these paths that are like forking,

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.000
and I choose to go one way, and that means I would end up in a different place at the end

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
than if I chose to go a different direction.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:15.000
So when we are in this iterative process, this means that the decisions that we make,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:21.000
as we're deciding, like as we're doing data analysis, they change where we may have ended up in the end.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:31.000
So this paper specifically talks about this idea of a labyrinth or a garden of forking paths

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:36.000
in the context of how we use p-values in a statistical sense.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:43.000
It talks about how dangerous it is to very naively use p-values when you've made a lot of decisions.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:46.000
But forking paths are a good thing.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:54.000
Like it is good to make decisions and we base our next decision on the last one we made.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:01.000
It is good to analyze data in different ways and to use what we learn about the data to do the next thing.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:10.000
The mistake actually would be to choose just one, like I'm doing this, and I decided,

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.000
I don't care what I see in the data, that's just what I'm like.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.000
I'm not going to use the information in the data itself.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:17.000
That would be a mistake.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:22.000
And another mistake is of the nature that is really focused on this paper,

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:29.000
would be, for example, to compute p-values without accounting for all the different choices we made.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:32.000
So the garden of forking paths is not a problem.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:37.000
It is the only option we have to correctly analyze data.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:45.000
But it means that as we move through a path, we end up at a place that would have been different

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
than if we took a different set of paths.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:54.000
So this is part of why we have this very exploratory kind of iterative nature of data work.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:00.000
Now, at the same time that that is happening, we as data scientists, people working with data,

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
we know we need really reproducible practices.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:11.000
And it turns out that the nature of computational data analysis has really exposed limitations

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:14.000
in our ability to evaluate findings.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:22.000
So this paper here explores what it means for a work to be reproducible.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:25.000
It explores it from a research or academic perspective.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:30.000
And it talks about this spectrum from, hey, I'm just telling you my results.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:34.000
So picture this as, like, you ran some code in a Jupyter notebook.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:39.000
And the cells are all out of order, actually, of, like, the order you ran them in.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:40.000
And you made a plot.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
And you posted the plot in Slack.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
And then, like, that's this side.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:45.000
That's this side.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:55.000
And then there's a full spectrum of reproducibility that takes us through, okay, I check my code into GitHub.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:59.000
And I use good practices about how I write my code.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:08.000
And, oh, maybe I even can go all the way over that side to maybe a fully reproducible or replicable kind of process.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:16.000
So by very nature of our data work, we have iterative, exploratory process.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:22.000
At the same time, there's tension because we have we need this reproducible practices.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
This was about academic research.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:27.000
But the same thing applies in a company or in an industry.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
And so we end up in this situation.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:35.000
The process of data science is inherently iterative and exploratory.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:40.000
And at the same time, we know we need these to adopt more reproducible practices.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
This is to maintain the integrity of our work.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:48.000
To show the people we work with that what we're doing can be relied on.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:52.000
That we it is efficacious.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:55.000
It is it does what we say it does.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:59.000
So these characteristics of data analysis work are in tension.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:03.000
And what I want to talk to you about today is this tension.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:10.000
And how the processes that we adopt and the tools we choose to use can bring those tensions into balance.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:19.000
So it is with this background and context that I want to tell you about a new IDE that I and my team have been working on.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
That is built specifically with this kind of tension in mind.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
So this is a screenshot of Positron.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
This new data science IDE.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
Positron has been available for beta testing for about the last year.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:36.000
And just this past week, actually, we moved to stable releases.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:37.000
Which is really exciting.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:40.000
So Positron is no longer a beta product.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
It's now a regularly available product.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.000
So I'm using the term IDE.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
That stands for integrated development environment.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:56.000
And that's a piece of software, you know, that allows you, as someone who writes code, to yourself develop software.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:12:03.000
So in this example, someone is writing a report using Cordo and Python.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:10.000
So on the left, you see the source code for the report that they're writing.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:18.000
And on the right, you see the rendered, finished version of the report that you might be able to publish or send to a coworker.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
So there are a lot of IDEs out there in the world.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:25.000
IDEs, code editors, you know, depending on what you might want to call these.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:31.000
And so I'm going to tell you today about what's new and or different about Positron.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
You know, so that, you know, I would be very happy if you tried it out.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:41.000
But more importantly, so that we can think about can you choose the right tool for the job you need to do?

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.000
Whatever that job is.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
Whether it's very iterative and exploratory.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:54.000
Or if you're someone who does more traditional software engineering, you can think about what is the right kind of tool for the kind of work that I do.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
So let's dig into this.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:07.000
The first thing that I want to say a little more about what I mean is that I'm going to tell you Positron is a next generation IDE specifically for data science.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So the company that I work at, Posit, is a company that makes Cordo.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
Like the developers at our company are the ones that make Cordo.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:30.000
We make Shiny, the Tidyverse, RStudio, open source packages in Python and R for things like making tables, doing machine learning, MLOps.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.000
So we think a lot.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
We are all about data science.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
The process of data science.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:49.000
And we think that we would say we know that someone who is writing code for data analysis or machine learning, that person is different from someone who is doing software engineering.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:53.000
We are huge proponents of code first data science.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:57.000
What I mean when I say that is that person writes code.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.000
They're not using a low code or no code tool.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:03.000
They're not pointy clicky, pointy clicky in a GUI.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
They're writing code.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:16.000
Tools that are built for a typical software engineer who is writing code, they're often not a good fit for someone who is writing code to analyze data.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:20.000
Because of that need for iteration and exploration.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:29.000
So all across our org, pretty much every single thing we make or do or build is informed by how deeply we know and believe kind of these two things.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
Code first data science.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
People who do data science are different.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:40.000
And we think we can make you, if you are a data practitioner, more productive with these tools because they're specifically built for the kinds of things you need to do.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
So this is why we're building this thing.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
Because there isn't something out there that is quite like this.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:49.000
A platform where you can do all of your data science.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:57.000
The second thing I want to dig into and talk to you about a little bit is that positron is what we call a polyglot or multilingual IDE.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:04.000
Currently at this period, it comes with first class data science support for both Python and for R.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:14.000
So a lot of environments that were built for data analysis are specifically built to use one language run time for scientific computing.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:20.000
So tools that you probably have heard about or used yourself that fall into this category include R studio.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
Include things like mat lab.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
Include things like spider.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
The Python IDE spider.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:36.000
There's a lot of these where all of the UI is super strongly linked to one kind of run time for scientific computing.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:40.000
And there are real limits to these kinds of tools or IDEs.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:48.000
Because it turns out a high proportion of people use multiple languages for data science or for their projects in general.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
This can happen literally on the same project.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.000
Like one project can involve multiple languages.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:59.000
This can happen over a week as you move from one project to another project.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
This project is in this language.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
This project is in another language.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:07.000
It almost certainly is going to happen over the span of your career.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
I know that it has in mind.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:21.000
When I think back to the kinds of programming languages I used when I was in astronomy, when I did, you know, like I look back, I see some real shifts in the languages that I have used over the course of my career.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:29.000
And for most people who are about my place, about the same place that I am in our careers, we all say the same thing.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:34.000
Very few of us picked one language and then used it our whole career.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
So I bet many of you are familiar with this.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:41.000
Maybe you build Python packages that involve a C code.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
So you're combining Python and C.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:46.000
Maybe you combine Python and JavaScript.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:49.000
Maybe you make complex interactive apps.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:53.000
And so you use Python plus a bit of JavaScript.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.000
Maybe you're someone who uses Python together with SQL.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:57.000
You write SQL queries.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:58.000
You have data.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
Then you use Python maybe for machine learning.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:04.000
Maybe, like me, you're someone who uses both R and Python.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:23.000
So by contrast with those kinds of IDEs or editors that I talked about before, Positron is built with front-end user-facing features that are about the tasks that you need to do when you're, like, analyzing data or doing other kinds of data-specific work.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:28.000
And then there are back-end language packs that are like the engine.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
They provide the engines for all those features and tasks.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:32.000
So here you see some of these.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
You see a fully interactive console.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:39.000
Much more fully featured than a typical Python REPL.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:43.000
A plots pane where you can interact with the plots that you make.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:46.000
A variables pane where you see all the variables you've defined.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
And in addition to the place where you're actually writing the code.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:53.000
So in this case, these are all backed by Python.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:18:01.000
But these front-end features are architecturally separate from the runtime that is the engine there.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:04.000
And that means today we have support for Python and R.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
But we can add in support for Julia.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:13.000
We can add in support for other scientific computing languages that become important in data science.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:26.000
So data practice, as I think about it based on my experience, it tends to involve three main categories of work that are qualitatively different from general purpose software engineering.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:30.000
So I'd say one category is exploratory data analysis.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
That's what I've really been talking about here.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
That iterative process.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:37.000
One piece is reproducible authoring.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:50.000
So this is kind of where we need to write some kind of report or make a website or make some kind of interactive app that depends on the data that we are presenting or analyzing or communicating about.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:58.000
We do not want to be in a situation where we're copying and pasting plots from inside of your editor into a Word document.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:01.000
We do not want to ever be in that situation.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:09.000
Instead, we want to build reproducible documents so that the whole document can create the report or the website or whatever it is that you need to make.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:13.000
And then that third category is publishing data artifacts.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:27.000
And this is often a challenge for people of data work because it kind of is at the edge of iterative scientific data work into more traditional software world because you're like trying to deploy something.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:46.000
As we kind of dig into this a little more, I want to say, I might say this more than once, but I really hope a big takeaway here for all of you is that it's not bad or wrong that people who are doing data work are different than people who are doing traditional software engineering work.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:59.000
If you're a data science person and you're like, gosh, yeah, like I feel a little bit like the software engineering person I work with, it is better that they do something different.

00:19:59.000 --> 00:20:01.000
It's not bad or wrong that it's different.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:02.000
It's just different.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:06.000
And that's reflective of the reality that the work is actually different.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:16.000
So you need tools, though, that are built specifically for the tasks you need to do, whether that is the data work or maybe more traditional engineering work.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:27.000
So I'm going to walk through a little bit more of the components of what makes Positron a bit unique so that you can understand how it kind of links to this iterative exploratory kind of work.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:42.000
So first I want to highlight that because we are in a world where we're writing code, we definitely have a place, there's a place in this ID where you write code in a traditional, in a very traditional way here.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:49.000
But not only do you need somewhere to write code, you also need somewhere to execute code interactively.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:54.000
You could think of this as like a sandbox or think of this sort of like a playground.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:21:07.000
It's a good place to test out code quickly and see the results in a truly interactive way so that you can get that quick feedback loop of what's going on with your code.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:17.000
Not because you are doing all your analysis in this interactive console, but because you have to see what the results are to know what the next step is.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:21.000
Because that is one of this nature of what data work is like.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:28.000
This is a, you can use keyboard shortcuts to run code from the file into the console.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:32.000
You get things like autocomplete and syntax highlighting in the console.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:36.000
Because again, this is real code that you're writing and running.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:43.000
It's a fully featured console that's connected to the other pieces of the IDE like the plots and the variables pane.

00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:52.000
And I'm not going to go into this in super detail right now, but here in this console, there's enhanced environment manager kind of support.

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:57.000
Where like interpreter management designed with an eye to these data science tasks.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:05.000
So that whatever Python interpreter it is that you have, you can easily understand what's going on with it.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:11.000
So we said that what's going on down here in the console is connected to the rest of the IDE.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:15.000
And this section over here is the variables pane.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:21.000
And this gives you a lot of information about every variable you have defined in the session that you're running right here.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:24.000
You get information about the type of the variable.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:28.000
You can see some of those guys are little tables because they're rectangular data structures.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:31.000
You'll see a little cylinder if you're dealing with a database connection.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:35.000
And the variables is connected like you see here to the console.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:40.000
But if you are someone who uses Jupyter notebooks, it's also connected there to the Jupyter notebook.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:44.000
It has another tab for each notebook session that you have.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:47.000
It's super handy for keeping clear.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:58.000
Like if you're running more than one Jupyter notebook at a time, it's super handy for understanding which session you're working with and what's going on here with that.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:02.000
This section down here is where you work with plots that you have.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:05.000
So you can dynamically create and update plots.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:09.000
You run code in the console, and then you see plots here.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:17.000
I am someone who finds this way easier for interactive work than, say, compared to a Jupyter notebook.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:24.000
It's kind of two different models for how to do this exploratory kind of interactive kind of work that you have here.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:30.000
It comes in handy when you have a lot of plots because of how easy it is to switch back between them.

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.000
You can see your iterations.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:33.000
You can say what you like.

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:41.000
Although I kind of bad-mouthed it a little bit ago, there is a button here where you just copy that plot, and then you can go and paste it in Slack.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:53.000
There's a lot of UI affordances here for exporting at certain sizes and for all the things that we know in real life happens with plots.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:58.000
Another feature that happens here in Positron is this data explorer.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:02.000
We think of this as a tool for debugging your data.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:06.000
So it supports Panda's data frames and Polar's data frames.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:17.000
And it's built in a way that is performant so that if you have something up to, say, tens of millions of rows and very wide data,

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:22.000
it's able to scroll around in ways that it doesn't hang the rest of the UI.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:28.000
And for each sort of column, you get summary statistics and spark lines where you can see what's going on.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:37.000
This is a really good way when you're in that iterative process of how do I know what's in my data so that I can then decide what code to write.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:41.000
This supports that kind of process.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:47.000
So you may see this and feel like, well, I've got a question here.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:53.000
Because you may say to me, you were talking about code-first data science, right?

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:59.000
And how does UI like this fit into that way of working?

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:08.000
And one of the things we're working on right now, actually, this month, is ways to, let's say you did some sort of filter and sort in here,

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:17.000
like as if you were in a spreadsheet type thing, a way to export the code that will get you that same, say, filtering and sorting.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:30.000
So we are all in on making sure that things are reproducible by making sure that we're focusing on code-first practices.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:36.000
Another component here is a viewer pane for viewing locally running content.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:39.000
So this is like a fully interactive kind of pane.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:46.000
Here on the left, we have a Streamlit app, and then it is running right there in the IDE on the right.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
You can view local host URLs.

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:52.000
You can open HTML files right there in the IDE.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:26:03.000
Run interactive apps like this one or, you know, FastAPI or Flask or Shiny or, like, other kinds of, like, HTML content here.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:09.000
This is where you can view a rendered document such as Cordo, like a rendered Cordo document you can see here.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:24.000
And I find this to be hugely impactful for my own work because you can end up in a flow state where you're able to edit the app or the document that you're working on

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:29.000
and automatically see it update versus having to go somewhere else to look at something.

00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:35.000
And we end up in this very tight feedback loop based on the code you're writing and the result that you're seeing.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:36.000
Okay.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:43.000
So as I'm walking through these features, I want to highlight that Positron is both familiar and it is extensible.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:50.000
And so it's familiar to some of you who are in this room because it's pretty directly inspired by RStudio.

00:26:50.000 --> 00:26:57.000
So many of the people who are working on Positron are the same people, like, literally the same people who have worked on RStudio.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:06.000
And here you see, like, a really RStudio-like interface with, you know, a console and a source editor and, like, a fully-featured help pane.

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:11.000
But it's being used in Python, you know, not in R as only would be possible in RStudio.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:22.000
So this help feature makes it really easy to find help for any function or package or topic that you have right from within the IDE

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:25.000
so you don't have to go and get distracted by the internet looking things up.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:29.000
Like, you get to see everything right there inside of the product.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:34.000
It supports interlinks between help topics and different packages.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:39.000
When you see examples, they have the syntax highlighting, really nice to be able to see it.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:45.000
I have found this to be as helpful as a user, but it's also helpful as a package developer.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:50.000
Because if you're working on your Python package and then you, you know, reload it, you build it locally,

00:27:50.000 --> 00:27:57.000
you can see the help that you just wrote right there in a way that keeps you in that tight feedback loop in this sort of flow state

00:27:57.000 --> 00:28:01.000
without having to leave the IDE to figure out how things are happening.

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:12.000
So it's also familiar to almost everyone in this room because it is built on the open-source components that are used to make Visual Studio Code.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:20.000
So Positron is a fork of the open-source project that Microsoft uses to make their proprietary builds of VS Code.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:25.000
This is similar to how Cursor and Windsurf are forks of this project.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:35.000
Now, building on Code OSS, as that project is called, we forked it for slightly different reasons than maybe Cursor and Windsurf did.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:44.000
We forked it because we see this as we are able to focus on the data science tasks, the data science features,

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:49.000
which is what we care about and what we really have some institutional muscle around.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:56.000
We do not have to spend our time working on the general features that every kind of person who writes code needs.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:29:02.000
So as an example, we have not changed the experience around the source editor.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:06.000
We have not changed the experience around how you interact with Git.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:10.000
We have built an entirely new, truly interactive console.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:16.000
We have built a new connected, integrated way to build with your plots.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:22.000
So building on Code OSS really allows us to focus on the things we care about,

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:30.000
and we kind of make a deal that we largely accept how things work in VS Code for other kinds of features.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:41.000
Building on Code OSS also opens up the wide world of VS Code-compatible extensions for users who want a data science-specific IDE.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:46.000
So this, you know, if you all are familiar, it's like any theme you can imagine.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:53.000
Make your editor look however you want to extensions that are more about maybe more substantive functionality,

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:57.000
like connecting to, you know, I don't know, Databricks or wherever your data is.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:04.000
And you also mean you can build extensions yourself that will work both in VS Code and in Positron.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:09.000
Now, if you're familiar with extensions of that nature, you may be thinking,

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:12.000
wait a minute, why didn't you just make extensions?

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:16.000
Why didn't you make, like, really good data science extensions?

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:18.000
And we have thought pretty carefully about this,

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:25.000
about what features need to be part of the sort of core product itself,

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:29.000
and what can we support more versus integration with extensions.

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:35.000
And at, you know, in my teams, at my company, we actually make a bunch of extensions.

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:38.000
We make an extension for Cordo, an extension for Shiny.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:42.000
We make an extension for Posit Connect, which is what's showing here.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:45.000
This Connect is a publishing platform for data science.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:49.000
And so this person has made a dashboard, and they're just mid-publishing.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:54.000
They're just in the process of publishing this Python dashboard to Posit Connect here.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:57.000
So we're all in on extensions.

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:05.000
And we're huge fans of the extension story around these kinds of IDEs.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:11.000
However, it turns out that not everything we need for a first-class data science experience

00:31:11.000 --> 00:31:14.000
can be built into extensions.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:20.000
And that's because of the very good reasons that the extension API is limited.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:23.000
And especially extensions cannot talk to each other,

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:27.000
and especially we cannot get the kind of fully integrated experience

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:31.000
on the kind of components that I just showed you.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:35.000
So these, like, deeply iterative workflows,

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:37.000
and that tension that I talked about,

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:40.000
like this deeply iterative workflow and the reproducible needs,

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:45.000
it turns out that solving that problem just with extensions,

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:47.000
you know, I'm going to argue, actually doesn't play out that well.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:50.000
And I bet this is resonating with some of you.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:54.000
If you are someone who does a lot of iterative, exploratory data work,

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:58.000
and you have tried to make VS Code into a data science IDE

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:01.000
with an extension pack or the data wrangler,

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:04.000
and you're like, yeah, okay, I'm getting it,

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:07.000
but you're like, but this doesn't update when this updates,

00:32:07.000 --> 00:32:09.000
and I can't now see this.

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:15.000
That's exactly why we actually forked instead of building sets of extensions.

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:21.000
So if I'm up here in the year 2025 talking about a new IDE,

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:25.000
I'm sure, I'm confident that a question at the top of many of your minds

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:31.000
is how and in what ways is Positron set up to work with LLMs.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.000
So I'm going to say it one more time.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:37.000
Positron is not a general purpose software engineering IDE.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:41.000
It is, so we don't see tools like Cursor and Windsurf

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:43.000
as our direct competitors,

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:47.000
because those are built, again, for general purpose software engineering,

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:49.000
and we're just not in that business.

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:53.000
Those are not the users that we are focused on and that we care about.

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:55.000
Instead, our goals here,

00:32:55.000 --> 00:33:00.000
and our goals around LLM code assistance and AI integrations,

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:04.000
our goals are to build an IDE specifically for data science,

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:06.000
for statistical analysis.

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:10.000
I'm just going to take a moment to talk a little bit about,

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:14.000
our company has been going through some pretty deep exploration

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:17.000
of what the rise of these new models means for our users,

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:22.000
and our open source users, our free and open source products,

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:26.000
our customers, the people who pay us for our enterprise software,

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:28.000
and even we ourselves.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:31.000
What does it mean for we ourselves at our company

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:35.000
to work in the era of these AI models?

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:38.000
So our company, one of the ways we've been exploring that

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:40.000
is with internal hackathons.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:42.000
They're a week long.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:44.000
You end up in a small group with people

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:47.000
who you maybe don't work with on a daily basis,

00:33:47.000 --> 00:33:49.000
and at the beginning of the week, there's an intro,

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.000
here are what these models are like,

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:55.000
and then each person commits to spending a certain number of hours

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:57.000
working on a small project.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:59.000
So this is my project,

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:02.000
my very small, little experimental project.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:06.000
I'll just highlight a little bit to give you an idea.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:11.000
I'm very interested in text analysis and NLP,

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:13.000
and have been for a very long time,

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:15.000
and so I was interested, A,

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:21.000
in how these models can be used for text analysis,

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:24.000
like how they can be used not only to generate text,

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:26.000
but to analyze text,

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:30.000
and B, I'm someone who's pretty concerned

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:32.000
about the way these models can be used

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:34.000
for disinformation at scale.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:36.000
And I was like, well, I wonder if I thought about it.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:38.000
Could I think of a way that these models can be used

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:42.000
to maybe counteract disinformation in some way?

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:45.000
And so this is a very small project, right?

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:50.000
But I built a dashboard that takes as its input a URL,

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:51.000
like any URL.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:53.000
It gets the content from the URL,

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:56.000
it summarizes it,

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:58.000
it goes to Wikipedia and finds

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:02.000
what Wikipedia pages are about this same topic.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:04.000
It gets the content from Wikipedia,

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:06.000
and then you end up at the end asking the model,

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:08.000
okay, you have this text,

00:35:08.000 --> 00:35:10.000
which is the text from the original URL.

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:12.000
You have this text, which is from Wikipedia.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:15.000
Can you comment, like tell me how well they agree?

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:17.000
And so you ask it to give it a score,

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:20.000
and then it writes a short paragraph

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:22.000
about whether they agree or disagree.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:24.000
So this example is a website

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:27.000
that spreads vaccine disinformation,

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:31.000
and this particular page is about the CDC

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:34.000
that it should study a link between vaccines and autism, right?

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:37.000
And so what my little project did

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:41.000
was help me get my hands dirty with the models

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:44.000
and help to understand what is it that they can do

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:47.000
and what is it that they actually cannot do right now.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:50.000
And it's been interesting to see people at my company in general

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:53.000
start to wrestle with these issues.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:55.000
And just briefly, I'll say,

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:59.000
people who are skeptics stay skeptical,

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:05.000
but they are more concrete about what they are skeptical about.

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:07.000
People who are enthusiasts,

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:10.000
they stay really enthusiastic about these kinds of models,

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:13.000
but they get more specific about what they are excited about.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:15.000
So it's been very interesting

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:18.000
seeing my company really wrestle with this,

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:20.000
and like what are we going to do?

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:23.000
Like what are we going to do with the tools that we make?

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:26.000
This paper came out in the past spring,

00:36:27.000 --> 00:36:30.000
and I highly recommend that you read this paper.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:33.000
It's like an opinion paper or a position paper,

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:38.000
and it makes the argument that AI is a normal technology.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.000
And so this is a quote.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:43.000
When they're saying AI is a normal technology,

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:46.000
they're not being like, oh, it's no big deal.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:48.000
They're saying it's a normal technology

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:51.000
in the same way that the Internet is a normal technology

00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:54.000
or electricity is a normal technology.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:59.000
So it's going to have a huge impact on how we work and learn and teach.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:02.000
It's not to understate its impact,

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:08.000
but instead to view it as a normal technology

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:13.000
is to contrast it both with the very utopian views

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:17.000
of what these models can bring and the very dystopian views,

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:21.000
and instead to give us tools from what we learned.

00:37:21.000 --> 00:37:25.000
Like what did we learn from the transition from before the Internet

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:26.000
to have the Internet?

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:31.000
What can we learn from history about bringing electricity?

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:32.000
How did that happen?

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:34.000
Who benefited?

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:35.000
Who was left behind?

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:38.000
We can learn from these things that happened in the past

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:41.000
to help us make better decisions about what's going on now

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:44.000
with this transition to AI.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:47.000
So how we think about AI and LLMs

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:50.000
is deeply informed by all this stuff we're thinking about

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:54.000
and this particular perspective on data science that we have.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.000
So we're asking questions like,

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:00.000
what do people who are doing statistic analysis need

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:02.000
when it comes to LLMs?

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:06.000
So to be clear, we're not training new models.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:10.000
We're not training Copilot, but for data science.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:11.000
We're not training new models.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:16.000
We instead are building tools of various kinds on top of the models.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:18.000
And so in the IDE, in Positron,

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:23.000
this looks like taking advantage of that deep integration

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:28.000
so that we can increase the context available to the LLM.

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:31.000
This includes things like chat participants

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:33.000
that are data science aware,

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:36.000
know about what is going on with data science projects

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:40.000
to scaffold you to getting more quickly what you need to do.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:45.000
So this is what Positron Assistant looks like.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:48.000
It is currently available in preview in Positron.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:50.000
And it can be run in three modes.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.000
The first mode is ask.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:55.000
So this is like a chat style.

00:38:55.000 --> 00:38:59.000
You're just like asking and it answers, ask answers,

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:01.000
like sort of chat GPT style.

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:04.000
Edit, so that's where you're in a file

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:06.000
and then you ask the model things about the file

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:08.000
and ask it to propose edits for you.

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:11.000
And then the third mode is agent.

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:14.000
So an agentic mode where you opt in

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:17.000
to giving the assistant permission

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:20.000
to run code on your behalf.

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:23.000
So the assistant gets to run code in the console

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:27.000
and it sees the results and I see the results.

00:39:27.000 --> 00:39:29.000
We both see the results of what happens here.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:34.000
And this ends up giving us like more context

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:35.000
and some pretty successful stuff.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:38.000
So here, I down here, I'm saying,

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:41.000
hey, I wanna read in some data

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:45.000
available at a certain CSV file here.

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:47.000
And if you'll notice up there,

00:39:47.000 --> 00:39:50.000
I imported Polars and I imported Seaborn here.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:52.000
And so what's gonna happen is

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:57.000
it is going to try to use Polars to read in the data.

00:39:57.000 --> 00:39:59.000
So here, this is my same, this is my prompt.

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:00.000
This is what I asked it to do.

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:03.000
And then you will notice that it's like,

00:40:03.000 --> 00:40:05.000
okay, great, here is some code.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:07.000
And it automatically ran it

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:09.000
because it's in this kind of agent mode.

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:11.000
But look, look what happened.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:13.000
An error, it didn't work.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:15.000
It didn't read in my CSV.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:20.000
Now, because we have this deeply integrated experience here,

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:23.000
what happens is that, I mean, obviously I see the error.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:24.000
I'm the one looking at the computer.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:27.000
But also, the assistant sees the error.

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:31.000
And notice there is no, I did not give any input

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:34.000
between that first step and this step.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:35.000
It sees the error and it's like,

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.000
oh, the error indicates that, you know,

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:41.000
like we didn't handle the NA values here that are in the CSV.

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:42.000
So let me try again.

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:45.000
And then if I hit that run code button,

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:47.000
it runs it again and then it succeeds.

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:50.000
I also want to highlight that it used Polars.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:52.000
And that's not because I prompted it,

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:53.000
or there's prompt,

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:55.000
like Positron is not all Polars all the time.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:57.000
It's because I imported it.

00:40:57.000 --> 00:40:58.000
So it knows to use,

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:01.000
it has deep integrated knowledge

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:04.000
of what's already going on in the IDE.

00:41:05.000 --> 00:41:06.000
So that it can generate the code

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:09.000
that you actually want it to generate.

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:13.000
So let's get that ugly error off the screen.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:14.000
Who wants to see errors in code?

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:17.000
So here, this is just us going a little further.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:19.000
And I'll highlight a few things.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.000
Like as I ask a question up at the top,

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:25.000
like hey, for these Pokemon that are in this data set,

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:27.000
like how are height and weight related?

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:30.000
And then the assistant generates some code

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:35.000
that uses Polars and then uses Seaborn to make plots,

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:37.000
because that's what I had already loaded.

00:41:37.000 --> 00:41:39.000
I didn't explicitly tell it to.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:41.000
It's using the context here.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:47.000
And also, like the assistant literally can view the plot.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:49.000
Like it takes the plot,

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:51.000
and the plot can get sent to the model.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:54.000
If you opt into permissions in such a way,

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:56.000
the plot itself gets,

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:58.000
because most of these multimodal models

00:41:58.000 --> 00:41:59.000
that are good at generating code,

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:02.000
they're multimodal and they can look at images,

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:04.000
and so they can describe plots for you,

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:06.000
tell you what's going on,

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:09.000
notice outliers, notice problems, and whatnot.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:13.000
So Positron Assistant,

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:18.000
I think it's a really interesting piece of the IDE,

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:22.000
because it highlights the outcomes that we're getting

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:25.000
by the sort of architecture we've chosen

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:29.000
and the set of trade-offs that we're making.

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:32.000
We are making trade-offs on the side of,

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:34.000
this is not for everyone.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:36.000
This is for people doing data science.

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:41.000
And that means it's powerful for the people doing data science,

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:43.000
because we're not trying to be everything to everyone.

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:45.000
We're trying to make the best thing

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:47.000
for people doing data science.

00:42:47.000 --> 00:42:50.000
And we are taking,

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:53.000
instead of everything is extensions,

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:57.000
we are saying what actually can improve the experience

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.000
by not being an extension

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:02.000
and being part of the IDE as a whole.

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:07.000
And so that, I will wrap up here a little bit

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:09.000
and say, hey, if this makes you curious,

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:11.000
if you want to try out Positron,

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:13.000
you can go to positron.posit.co.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:17.000
That's where you can get documentation and installers.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:20.000
If you run into bugs, if you have questions,

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:22.000
if you want to give us feedback,

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:26.000
join us on GitHub at posit-dev-positron.

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:28.000
If you are, I mean, I don't know,

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:30.000
if any of you are customers of ours,

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:33.000
Positron is available in Posit Workbench and Preview,

00:43:33.000 --> 00:43:35.000
which is one of our enterprise products

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:38.000
for big companies who need these kinds of features.

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:41.000
And if you're sitting in here

00:43:41.000 --> 00:43:44.000
and you're maybe not a data science person,

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:46.000
maybe you are one of these people

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:49.000
that uses Python more for traditional software engineering,

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:53.000
I do think a takeaway we can all take from here

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:59.000
is that not all software is built for the same purposes.

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:04.000
And so software tools that bring us joy

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:06.000
are not one-size-fits-all.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:09.000
But rather, we can build tools that are specifically

00:44:09.000 --> 00:44:11.000
for the kind of work that we need to do.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.000
And with that, I will say thank you very much.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:14.000
Thank you.

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:15.000
Thank you.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:16.000
Thank you very much.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:16.000


00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:44.000
Thank you.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:45.000
Thank you.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:46.000
Thank you.

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:46.000


